When I make {{POST => /rest/api/2/search}} request with params:

{code}
array(
  ["jql"] => "issuekey in (XXX-1)"
  ["expand"] => "transitions.fields"
  ["fields"] => array( "*all" )
  ["maxResults"] => "-1"
)
{code}

I get in my response:

{code}
array(1) {
  [0]=>
  array(5) {
    ["expand"]=>
    string(56) "editmeta,renderedFields,transitions,changelog,operations"
    // ...
    }
}
{code}

There is {{transitions}} in {{expand}}, but no transitions are included in issue data. When I explicitely define {{expand=transitions.fields}} in my search request I get an error (400 Bad Request).

Additionally, when I make request to {{issue/XXX-1}} (basically the same as in search request) with {{expand=transitions.fields}}, I get XXX-1 issue with -all- transitions information (edit: Ok, not all, only list of available transitions, without transition fields, so it does not work neither for single issue).

{{expand=transitions.fields}} should work for single issue request and for "bulk" issue search. In our case we need to know available transitions (with required fields) of every issue matched to our conditions (and retrieved via API request) so it wouldn't be optimal to make request for transitions for every single issue found earlier, especially that those request are real-time for user's request

The [ApplicationLinkMatcher class|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/atlassian-whitelist/src/9ba2728450d8fe880d3d30e74cc0c75a427e66fb/atlassian-whitelist-api-plugin/src/main/java/com/atlassian/plugins/whitelist/applinks/ApplicationLinkMatcher.java?at=master] and the [SelfUrlMatcher class|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/atlassian-whitelist/src/9ba2728450d8fe880d3d30e74cc0c75a427e66fb/atlassian-whitelist-api-plugin/src/main/java/com/atlassian/plugins/whitelist/matcher/SelfUrlMatcher.java?at=master#cl-32]
atlassian-whitelist-api-plugin considers a uri that *starts with* an application link's 'rpcurl' or *starts with* the current application's URI as a match respectively. When an application or an application link's 'rpcurl' does not contain a trailing '/' (e.g. https://foobar.com) and it does not explicitly specify a port then a uri of a domain that starts with either the current application or a application link's domain (and scheme) is considered valid. For example, if https://foobar.com is a configured application link then https://foobar.com.attacker.domain is matched and allowed. 

The atlassian-whitelist-api-plugin includes a [CorsFilter|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/atlassian-whitelist/src/9ba2728450d8fe880d3d30e74cc0c75a427e66fb/atlassian-whitelist-api-plugin/src/main/java/com/atlassian/plugins/cors/CorsFilter.java?at=master] which adds CORS headers to whitelisted origin responses that are under its configured url path (/rest/*). The CORS headers the CorsFilter adds allow CORS requests to be sent with credentials and set a custom content-type header. 

*Impact*
Where a context path or a port is not specified for the current application or a application link, an attacker can setup a site such that they can make CORS requests in a victim's browser to JIRA's rest api (read and write from JIRA's rest api). As the CORS response headers will permit a CORS request with a custom content-type header XSRF/CSRF protection depending upon the content-type header of an incoming request can be bypassed.

*How to fix:*
The in addition to the URI path the scheme, domain and port should be used to check if a uri matches an application link. e.g.
For ApplicationLinkMatcher
{code}

    @Override
    public boolean apply(final URI uri)
    {
        try
        {
            final URI normalizedUri = MatcherUtils.normalizeUri(uri);
           return (applinkRpcUrl.getHost().equals(normalizedUri.getHost()) && 
applinkRpcUrl.getScheme().equals(normalizedUri.getScheme()) && 
applinkRpcUrl.getPort() == normalizedUri.getPort() &&  
applinkRpcUrl.getPath().equals(uri.getPath()))

        }
        catch (URISyntaxException e)
        {
            return false;
        }
{code}

For SelfUrlMatcher:
{code}
    @Override
    public boolean apply(final URI uri)
    {
        try
        {
            final URI normalizedUri = MatcherUtils.normalizeUri(uri);
            final String baseUrl = Strings.nullToEmpty(applicationProperties.getBaseUrl(UrlMode.CANONICAL));
           return (baseUrl.getHost().equals(normalizedUri.getHost()) && 
baseUrl.getScheme().equals(normalizedUri.getScheme()) && 
baseUrl.getPort() == normalizedUri.getPort() &&  
baseUrl.getPath().equals(uri.getPath()))
        }
        catch (URISyntaxException e)
        {
            return false;
        }
    }
{code}

Also the URI path comparison check is not overly useful when used in the CorsFilter because "The Origin header includes only the information required to identify the principal that initiated the request (typically the scheme, host, and port of initiating origin). In particular, the Origin header does not contain the path or query portions of the URI included in the Referer header that invade privacy without providing additional security." (http://tools.ietf.org/id/draft-abarth-origin-03.html)

Note: JIRA implicitly trusts itself and so if JIRA is configured with an empty context path, e.g. http://jira.domain.com, then this issue can be exploited without any configured application links.

In the documentation for the [/rest/api/2/search|https://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/latest/#d2e5109] API call, we have the following:

{quote}
Request query parameters:

fields - the list of fields to return for each issue. By default, all navigable fields are returned.
{quote}

However, it seems the issue Key is always displayed, no matter what you set in the fields. For example:

{code:sql}
https://clarissa.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/search?jql=%28project=atp%29&fields=id,summary
{code}

It returns:

{code:xml}
{"expand":"editmeta,renderedFields,transitions,changelog,operations","id":"11011","self":"https://clarissa.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/11011","key":"ATP-999","fields":{"summary":"Test Summary)"
{code}

h3. Summary
Error message when Updating issues via CSV Importer logs:
{quote}
ERROR - Issue can't be created due to the error/s .. <error message>
{quote}
but no issues are being created, only updated.
This is misleading to users trying to understand what caused the error.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Do an export of an actual issue from an Issue Search
# Do a CSV import with the same information but causing it to fail by removing a Required field for example

h3. Expected Results
Error message displays:
{noformat}
ERROR - Issue can't be created/updated due to the error/s ..
{noformat}

h3. Actual Results
{noformat}
ERROR - Issue can't be created due to the error/s ..
{noformat}

h3. Summary
If a user is set as the reporter for an issue collector and that user has their username updated, the issue collector still uses the old username. The issue collector then fails when submitting feedback and shows an AJAX error.

h3. Environment
Cloud

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create an Issue Collector and set the reporter as an existing user
# Deploy the Issue Collector code to an existing page or file
# Edit the user set as the Reporter and change the username
# Submit feedback via the issue collector

h3. Expected Results
The Issue Collector will use the updated username as the reporter\\

h3. Actual Results
The Issue Collector attempts to use the old username and trying to submit feedback via the collector fails.

